                            <comment id="20470" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Thu, 26 Oct 2006 06:03:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I wasn&apos;t aware that a WebLogic Destination object always implements both the Queue interface and the Topic interface. There are few checks within Spring&apos;s JMS code that should be refined then. I have changed the one in AbstractMessageListenerContainer to check for (destination instanceof Topic &amp;amp;&amp;amp; !(destination instanceof Queue)) instead.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20483" author="springahead" created="Fri, 27 Oct 2006 00:12:08 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hello Juergen,&lt;br/&gt;
I looked at your solution and thought very slick. But it occurred to me afterwards that the solution will not work for a Topic. The reason is because of the awkward BEA implementation - weblogic.jms.common.DestinationImpl class implements both javax.jms.Queue and javax.jms.Topic.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So for a Topic the result will be false.&lt;br/&gt;
(destination instanceof Topic &amp;amp;&amp;amp; !(destination instanceof Queue)) &lt;br/&gt;
(true &amp;amp;&amp;amp; !(true)) &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I tested the code locally and discovered that this is the case.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kevin&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20487" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Fri, 27 Oct 2006 02:06:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Indeed, this needs a slight refinement for that case:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;  if (destination instanceof Topic &amp;amp;&amp;amp; !(destination instanceof Queue)) &lt;/p&gt;
{
    setPubSubDomain(true);
  }

&lt;p&gt;So only if we can clearly determine a Topic, we&apos;ll set the flag. Else we rely on the user-specific &quot;pubSubDomain&quot; value (if any).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This should work for the &quot;pubSubDomain&quot; value specified before the &quot;destination&quot; value as well now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
